hints_latex:
Remember that all vectors lying in the tangent plane to $z = f(x,y)$ are
perpendicular to the normal vector to the surface at the same point.
I.e., let $(x,y,z) = (x_{0},y_{0},z_{0})$ be a point on the surface of
$z = f(x,y)$. If $\mathbf{n}$ is the normal vector to $z = f(x,y)$ at
this point, then

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{n}\cdot \mathbf{v} = \mathbf{0}, \quad \mbox{where} \quad \mathbf{v} = \begin{bmatrix} x - x_{0} \\ y - y_{0} \\ z - z_{0}\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}
gives the equation of the tangent plane to the surface at the point
$(x_{0},y_{0},z_{0})$.

In this case, the normal vector, $\mathbf{n}$, is determined by the
gradient of function $F(x,y,z) = f(x,y) - z = 0$:

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{n} = \nabla F(x,y,z) = \begin{bmatrix}f_{x}(x,y) \\ f_{y}(x,y) \\ -1 \end{bmatrix}.
\end{align*}

sols_latex:
The equation of the tangent plane is given by evaluating

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{n}\cdot\mathbf{v} = 0
\end{align*} where
$\mathbf{v} = [x - 2, y - 1, z - f(2,1)]^{T}$ and $\mathbf{n}$ is a
normal vector to the surface $z = f(x,y)$ at $(x,y) = (2,1)$. The normal
vector at the point $(x,y)$ is given by

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{n}(x,y) = \begin{bmatrix}f_{x}(x,y) \\ f_{y}(x,y) \\ -1\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -2x e^{-x^2+4y^2} \\ 8y e^{-x^2+4y^2} \\ -1\end{bmatrix} \quad \rightarrow \quad \mathbf{n}(2,1) = \begin{bmatrix} -4 \\ 8 \\ -1\end{bmatrix}.
\end{align*}
Evaluating $\mathbf{n}\cdot\mathbf{v} = 0$ gives

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{n}\cdot\mathbf{v} = -4(x - 2) + 8(y - 1) -1(z - 1) = 0.
\end{align*} We
simplify the above equation (although it is not necessary) and get the
tangent plane to $f(x,y)$ at $(2,1)$:

\begin{align*}
{\color{blue} -4x + 8y - z = -1.}
\end{align*}

We can also get the tangent plane by using a linear Taylor
approximation. Recall for a function $\displaystyle {}f(x,y)$ we have the
linear approximation at a point $\displaystyle {}(x_0,y_0)$ is

\begin{align*}
f(x,y)\approx{}f(x_0,y_0)+\frac{\partial{}f}{\partial{}x}(x_0,y_0)(x-x_0)+\frac{\partial{}f}{\partial{}y}(x_0,y_0)(y-y_0).
\end{align*}

We are given that we want to approximate $\displaystyle {}f(2,1)$ and so
$\displaystyle {}x_0=2$ and $\displaystyle {}y_0=1$. We have

\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial{}f}{\partial{}x}&=-2x\textrm{e}^{-x^2+4y^2}\\
\frac{\partial{}f}{\partial{}y}&=8y\textrm{e}^{-x^2+4y^2}
\end{align*}

and so

\begin{align*}
f(2,1)&=1\\
\frac{\partial{}f}{\partial{}x}(2,1)&=-4\\
\frac{\partial{}f}{\partial{}y}(2,1)&=8.
\end{align*}

Since $\displaystyle {}z=f(x,y)$ we have

\begin{align*}
z&=1-4(x-2)+8(y-1)\\
0&=-4(x-2)+8(y-1)-(z-1)
\end{align*}

as the tangent plane approximation at the desired point.

